Money Stuff =0A Sometimes a company owes its creditors more money than it c=
an pay them, so it =0Afiles for bankruptcy. Loosely speaking, bankruptcy me=
ans that =0A=0A=0A =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/authors/ARbTQlRLRj=
E/matthew-s-levine=3Fcmpid=3DBBD121124_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_so=
urce=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D241211&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A =0A<https=
://sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D825881&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D11993146&m=3D21=
d6dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D12112024>=0A=0A=0A=0AGlobal Tetrahedron=
=0A=0ASometimes a company owes its creditors more money than it can pay the=
m, so it =0Afiles for bankruptcy. Loosely speaking, bankruptcy means that t=
he creditors own =0Athe company, and a bankruptcy court works out the best =
way to get them as much =0Avalue as possible. Often this means running an a=
uction for the company=E2=80=99s assets.=0A=0AIntuitively, the way the auct=
ion should work is that whoever bids the most for =0Athe assets gets to buy=
