dron</h2> </td> </tr> </table> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes a com=
pany owes its creditors more money than it can pay them, so it files for ba=
nkruptcy. Loosely speaking, bankruptcy means that the creditors own the com=
pany, and a bankruptcy court works out the best way to get them as much val=
ue as possible. Often this means running an auction for the company=E2=80=
=99s assets.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively, the way the auct=
ion should work is that whoever bids the most for the assets gets to buy th=
em, and then the creditors get the=C2=A0money. The creditors want as much m=
oney as possible, so they should sell to the highest bidder.</p> <p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is an important wrinkle here, though: What if on=
e of the creditors wants to buy the assets=3F Say the company owes a total =
of $100 million to four creditors. Creditor A and Creditor B each own=C2=A0=
$25 million of senior secured bonds, while Creditor C and Creditor D each o=
wn $25 million of junior unsecured bonds. (The senior secured bonds have to=
 be paid back in full before the junior bondholders get anything.) It goes =
bankrupt and puts its assets up for auction. Bidder E comes in and bids $40=
 million for the assets, which would result in Creditors A and B each getti=
ng $20 million (a 20% haircut on their bonds) and Creditors C and D each ge=
tting nothing. Creditor A says =E2=80=9Cnah the assets are worth more than =
that=E2=80=9D and bids $60 million, which would result in Creditors A and B=
 each getting paid back their full $25 million and Creditors C and D each g=
etting $5 million. Creditor A=E2=80=99s bid is the highest =E2=80=94=C2=A0$=
60 million is more than $40 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it wins the auction a=
nd gets the assets.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the court say=
s =E2=80=9Cgreat you won the auction, we=E2=80=99ll need a check for $60 mi=
llion=E2=80=9D and Creditor A says =E2=80=9Cno actually I=E2=80=99m owed $2=
5 million, and $25 million of my bid would go right back to me, so I=E2=80=
=99m just going to write a check for $35 million.=E2=80=9D And the court is=
 like =E2=80=9Coh right that makes sense,=E2=80=9D takes the $35 million, g=
ives $25 million of it to Creditor B and divides the rest among Creditors C=
 and D.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called a =E2=80=9Ccredit b=
id=E2=80=9D<a href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
