ant; display: inline-block;"> <span>[1]</span> </a>: Creditor A=E2=80=99s $=
60 million bid for the company was made up of (1) $35 million in cash and (=
2) $25 million of its own claim in bankruptcy.=C2=A0You could imagine Bidde=
r E being aggrieved. It might say:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CWait, I was willing to pay=
 $40 million, but Creditor A only paid $35 million and won the auction. Tha=
t=E2=80=99s no fair.=E2=80=9D But that is not a particularly good argument.=
 Creditor A=E2=80=99s bid was obviously better than Bidder E=E2=80=99s, bec=
ause it recovered more money for the (non-Creditor A) creditors.</p> <p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if Creditor C =E2=80=94=C2=A0a junior unsecured=
 bondholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0said =E2=80=9Cnah, the assets are worth even mor=
e than that=E2=80=9D and bid $70 million for them=3F Well, $70 million is m=
ore than $60 million, so Creditor C would win the auction. And then the cou=
rt would say =E2=80=9Cokay we=E2=80=99ll need a check for $70 million.=E2=
=80=9D And then Creditor C might reply =E2=80=9Cno actually I=E2=80=99m owe=
d $25 million, so here=E2=80=99s a check for $45 million.=E2=80=9D But that=
 doesn=E2=80=99t work! Creditor C=E2=80=99s $25 million claim=C2=A0<em>isn=
=E2=80=99t worth $25 million=C2=A0</em>to the bankruptcy estate, so it can=
=E2=80=99t get full credit for it. If Creditor C wrote a check for $45 mill=
ion, Creditors A and B wouldn=E2=80=99t get all of their money back (and Cr=
editor D would get nothing). Creditor A=E2=80=99s bid ($35 million cash, $6=
0 million total) is still better than Creditor C=E2=80=99s bid ($45 million=
 cash, $70 million total, but with that $70 million somewhat suspect).</p> =
